 Planning Department, Public Affairs and Statistics Section, Takaoka Shisei Gaiy\u014d T\u014dkei Sho \uff08\u9ad8\u5ca1\u5e02\u653f\u6982\u8981\u7d71\u8a08\u66f8\uff09, Takaoka City, 2010</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe area of present-day Takaoka was part of ancient [[Etch\u016b Province]], and the [[kokufu|provincial capital]] was located in what are now the outskirts of the modern city. [[\u014ctomo no Yakamochi]] took position as a government official in this area in the 8th century. During his five-year stay he wrote many [[waka (poetry)|''waka'' poems]]<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =  https://www.britannica.com/biography/Otomo-Yakamochi\n  | title = \u014ctomo Yakamochi - Japanese poet - Britannica.com\n  | publisher = Encyclopedia Britannica\n  | accessdate = 2018-04-06}}</ref>. This is the reason for Takaoka being nicknamed [[Man'y\u014dsh\u016b|Many\u014d City]]. \n\nOriginally, the Takaoka region was called ''Sekino'', but when [[Maeda Toshinaga]] of [[Kaga Domain]] took control of the city in 1609, he named it after a verse from the religious poem ''Shihen'' which includes the word ''Takaoka''. In addition to this, the fact that [[Takaoka Castle]] was built on a slightly elevated shoreline is thought to be another possible origin for the name Takaoka, since ''Taka'' means \"high\" and \"Oka\" means \"hill or elevated land\".\n\nDespite the loss of its castle due to orders from the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] in 1615, the [[Maeda clan]] pursued policies regulating the relocation of Takaoka citizens and promoting the development of Takaoka as an industrial city. This resulted in the start of Takaoka's role as a city of commerce and industry. Takaoka copperware and lacquerware also took off at this time.\nFollowing the [[Meiji restoration]], with the establishment of the municipalities system on April 1, 1889, Takaoka was registered as one of Japan's first 30 cities.<ref>Takaoka City Editorial Committee, Takaoka Rekishi to no Deai \uff08\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u306e\u51fa\u4f1a\u3044\uff09, Takaoka City, 1991, p.239</ref> The area around [[Fushiki Port]] was declared an open port for foreign trade by Imperial decree in July 1899.<ref>US Department of State. (1906). [https://books.google.com/books?id=dKCOAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA759&dq=  ''A digest of international law as embodied in diplomatic discussions, treaties and other international agreements'' (John Bassett Moore, ed.), Vol. 5, p. 759].</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2005, the town of [[Fukuoka, Toyama|Fukuoka]] (from [[Nishitonami District, Toyama|Nishitonami District]]) was merged into Takaoka. Therefore, Nishitonami District was dissolved as a result of this merger.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | url =  http://www.kokudo.or.jp/marge/tdfk.php?tdfk_cd=16\n  | title = \u90fd\u9053\u5e9c\u770c\u5225\u5e02\u753a\u6751\u5909\u66f4\u60c5\u5831\uff1a\u5bcc\u5c71\u770c\uff08in Japanese\uff09\n  | publisher = Japan Geographic Data Center\uff08\u516c\u76ca\u8ca1\u56e3\u6cd5\u4eba\u56fd\u571f\u5730\u7406\u5354\u4f1a\uff09\n  | accessdate = 2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Government==\nTakaoka has a [[mayor-council]] form of government with a directly elected mayor and a [[unicameral]] city legislature of 27 members. The city contributes seven members to the Toyama Prefectural Assembly. In terms of national politics, the city is part of the Toyama Third Electoral District for the [[House of Representatives (Japan)|lower house]] of the [[Diet of Japan]].\n\n==Education==\n===Colleges and universities===\n*[[Toyama University]] \u2013 Takaoka campus\n*[[Takaoka University of Law]]\n\n===Primary and secondary education===\nTakaoka has 26 public elementary schools and 12 public junior high schools operated by the town government, and eight public high schools operated by the Toyama Prefectural Board of Education. There are also three private high schools. The city also operates one special education school,<ref>[http://www.city.takaoka.toyama.jp/school/kosodate/gakko/gakkosyozaichi.html Official home page - Listing of schools in Takaoka]{{in lang|ja}}</ref> and an additional four special education schools are operated by the Toyama Prefectural government.\n\n==Transportation==\n===Railway===\n*[[File:JR logo (west).svg|22px]][[West Japan Railway Company]] (JR West)  - [[Hokuriku Shinkansen]]\n**{{STN|Shin-Takaoka}}\n*[[File:JR logo (west).svg|22px]][[West Japan Railway Company]] (JR West)  - [[Himi Line]]\n** {{STN|Takaoka|Toyama}} - {{STN|Etch\u016b-Nakagawa}} - {{STN|N\u014dmachi}} - {{STN|Fushiki}} - {{STN|Etch\u016b-Kokubu}} - {{STN|Amaharashi}}\n*[[File:JR logo (west).svg|22px]][[West Japan Railway Company]] (JR West) - [[J\u014dhana Line]]\n**{{STN|Takaoka|Toyama}} - ({{STN|Shin-Takaoka}}) - {{STN|Futatsuka}} - {{STN|Hayashi}} - {{STN|Toide}}\n*[[file:Ainokaze Toyama Railway logo.png|22px]] [[Ainokaze Toyama Railway]]\n**[[Fukuoka Station|Fukuoka]] - [[Nishi-Takaoka Station|Nishi-Takaoka]] - ({{STN|Takaoka-Yabunami}}) - {{STN|Takaoka|Toyama}}\n*[[Manyosen]] - [[Man'y\u014dsen Takaoka Kid\u014d Line]]\n**{{STN|Takaoka|Manyosen|Takaoka Station}} - {{STN|Suehiroch\u014d|Toyama}} - {{STN|Kataharamachi|Toyama}} - {{STN|Sakashitamachi}} - {{STN|Ky\u016bkan Iry\u014d Center-mae}} - {{STN|Hirok\u014dji|Toyama}} - {{STN|Shikino Ch\u016bgakk\u014d-mae}} - {{STN|Shimin By\u014din-mae|Toyama}} - {{STN|Ejiri}} - {{STN|Asahigaoka|Toyama}} - {{STN|Ogino|Toyama}} - {{STN|Shin-N\u014dmachi}} - {{STN|Yonejimaguchi}} -{{STN|N\u014dmachiguchi}} - {{STN|Shin-Yoshihisa}} - {{STN|Yoshihisa}}\n*[[Manyosen]] - [[Man'y\u014dsen Shinminatok\u014d Line]]\n**{{STN|Naka Shinminato }}\n\n===Highway===\n*[[Hokuriku Expressway]]\n* {{jct|country=JPN|Route|8}}\n* {{jct|country=JPN|Route|156}}\n* {{jct|country=JPN|Route|160}}\n* {{jct|country=JPN|Route|415}}\n\n==International relations==\n*{{Flagicon|Brazil}} [[Mirand\u00f3polis]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo (state)|S\u00e3o Paulo]], Brazil, since 1974 <ref name= \"profile\">[http://www.city.takaoka.toyama.jp/joho/shise/gaiyo/gaiyo.html#m04 Takaoka City Profile]{{in lang|ja}}</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|US}} [[Fort Wayne, Indiana]], United States, since 1977<ref>http://www.fortwaynesistercities.net/</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|China}} [[Jinzhou]], [[Liaoning]], China, friendship city since August 1985 <ref name= \"profile\"/>\n*{{Flagicon|China}} [[Liaoyang]], [[Liaoning]], China, friendship city since August 2010\n\n==Local attractions==\n[[File:TakaokaDaibutsu.jpg|left|thumb|Great Buddha of Takaoka]]\n*'''The Great Buddha of Takaoka'''\nReaching a height of nearly 16 m, the Great Buddha of Takaoka is the third largest in Japan. The current Buddha made of Takaoka bronze was completed in 1933 after the previous statue made of wood burnt down. The Buddha is situated next to the Daibutsu Temple in the middle of a residential area in Takaoka town centre.\n*'''Kojo Park'''\nKojo Park, the former site of the Takaoka Castle, is situated a short walk from the centre of Takaoka. Within the park grounds there are the Imizu Shrine, the Takaoka Museum, Takaoka Zoo, the Civic Hall, and Civic Gymnasium plus abundant nature. The moat surrounding the centre of the park is a common spot for cherry blossom viewing in spring.\n\n[[File:Zuiryuji Temple 2010-08-29 01.jpg|left|thumb|Zuiry\u016bji Temple]]\n*'''Zuiry\u016b-ji Temple'''\nCompleted in 1663, [[Zuiry\u016b-ji (Toyama)|Zuiry\u016b-ji]] temple, is just south of Takaoka Station and a designated [[National Treasure of Japan]]. This Zen temple was constructed to mourn for the death of Maeda Toshinaga who fortified Takaoka and is celebrated as being reminiscent of architecture from the early [[Edo period]].\n*'''The Amaharashi Coast'''\nThe Amaharashi Coast, located north of Takaoka city has sandy beaches and views of the Onnaiwa Rock against the backdrop of the Tateyama mountains.\n*'''Kanayamachi'''\nKanayamachi is an area of Takaoka which has traditional buildings, both warehouses and houses, which have been preserved since the Meiji period. It is the birthplace of the manufacture of Takaoka copperware.\n*'''Sakuradani kofun'''\nThe [[Sakuradani Kofun]] is group of ''[[kofun]]'' [[burial mound]]s, two of which are designated as a [[Monuments of Japan|National Historic Site of Japan]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/216289 |script-title=ja:\u685c\u8c37\u53e4\u58b3\u7fa4 |trans-title= Sakuradani kofun gun|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Festivals==\n*'''Takaoka Mikurumayama Festival''' (May 1)\nThe tradition of this festival started when [[Maeda Toshinaga]] received a float from Hideyoshi, a powerful figure at the time, and gave it to the people of Takaoka. The festival features seven floats, crafted in the brightly colored ''Momoyama'' style, which make their way around the streets of Takaoka.<ref>Takaoka City Editorial Committee, Takaoka Rekishi to no Deai \uff08\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u306e\u51fa\u4f1a\u3044\uff09, Takaoka City, 1991, p.207</ref>\n*'''Fushiki Hikiyama Festival''' (May 15)\nThe Hikiyama festival in the port town of Fushiki is called \u2018Kenkayama\u2019 (fighting floats) by locals. During the day the floats are adorned with flowers, and at night they are decorated with paper lanterns. The floats are rammed into each other to the beat of the yamaga war drums.\n*'''Goin Festival''' (June 19/20)\nThe Goin festival celebrates the kindness of Maeda Toshinaga who took care of the city's casters, by worshipping documents with his seal on. During the festival, the Yagaefu dance (a processional dance performed with bamboo sticks) is also performed on the streets of Kanayamachi.\n\n[[File:Toide tanabata1.jpg|right|thumb|Toide Tanabata Festival (Toide, Takaoka)]]\n*'''Toide Tanabata Festival''' (July 3\u20137)\nA large collection of around 1,000 ''tanabata'' of various sizes, including 20 m tall jumbo tanabata, make a large tunnel that serves as an archway into the town's main street.\n*'''Takaoka Tanabata Festival''' (Early August)\nThe Takaoka Tanabata Festival is a symbol of summertime, when the streets are lined with thousands of large tanabata to celebrate the union of Orihime and Hikoboshi, two deities who, according to legend, are only allowed to meet once a year.\n*'''Fukuoka Machi Tsukurimon Festival''' (23/24 September)\nThe Tsukurimon festival is a festival with over 300 years of history. Sculptures depicting local sights and famous characters are made out of fruits and vegetables and displayed throughout the town.\n*'''Nakada Scarecrow Festival''' (late September)\nDepicting current events and famous characters, scarecrows are made using everyday materials such as straw and wood and displayed around the main shopping area of the Nakada district.\n*'''Takaoka Many\u014d Festival''' (first weekend of October)\nThis major autumn event celebrates the Many\u014d tradition with a marathon poetry recital lasting three days and three nights. The entire Many\u014d poetry anthology is recited by a large number of participants in a relay fashion.\n*'''Takaoka Nabe Festival''' (mid January)\nFresh fish and shellfish from the Sea of Japan are cooked in large cauldrons made with local casting techniques.\n\n==Notable people from Takaoka==\n*[[Takamine J\u014dkichi]] (1854&ndash;1922), scientist specializing in engineering and pharmacology. Joint founder of the RIKEN Natural Sciences Institute and discoverer of Adrenaline.\n*[[Sosen Mishima]] (1876&ndash;1934), author and theatre critic whose career took off at the start of the 20th century after his work \u2018Kaiboshitsu\u2019 (Dissecting Room) was published in the Chuo Koron literary magazine.\n*Kingetsu Murozaki (1891&ndash;1977), composer and founder of the Chuo School of Music, Tokyo. Known for \u2018Yuhi\u2019 (Sunset), a song which he wrote about the view of sunset at Takaoka's Kojo Park.<ref>Takaoka Lifelong Learning Web, http://www.manabi-takaoka.jp/03/eng/category/detail/1062/2/detail.html</ref>\n*Eichi Kanamori (1908&ndash;2001), a recognized Important Intangible Cultural Asset (a \u201cLiving National Treasure\u201d) as a leading metal engraver of Takaoka copperware.<ref>Takaoka City Editorial Committee, Takaoka Rekishi to no Deai \uff08\u6b74\u53f2\u3068\u306e\u51fa\u4f1a\u3044\uff09, Takaoka City, 1991, p.321</ref>\n*[[Fujiko Fujio]] (1933&ndash;1996), the pen name of Hiroshi Fujimoto, who together with and Abiko Motoo, created several characters including the world-famous \u2018[[Doraemon]]\u2019.\n*Komin Ozawa (born 1941), a recognized Important Intangible Cultural Asset (a \u201cLiving National Treasure\u201d), Ozawa is known as the master of the Chukin casting technique of making utensils and vessels by pouring molten metal into a mould.<ref>Takaoka Lifelong Learning Web, http://www.manabi-takaoka.jp/03/jpn/category/detail/1883/1/detail.html</ref>\n*[[Y\u014djir\u014d Takita]] (born 1955), filmmaker whose 2008 film ''[[Departures (2008 film)|Okuribito]]'' won a US Academy award for Best Foreign Language Film.\n*[[Izumi Matsumoto]], manga artist\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* [http://www.manabi-takaoka.jp/en_index.html Takaoka Lifelong Learning Web]\n{{refend}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.city.takaoka.toyama.jp/keiei/kurashi/gaikoku/english.html Takaoka City official website] \n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070714091329/http://sightseeing.in-japan.jp/2007/06/takaoka_daibutsu.html An article about the Takaoka Daibutsu]\n* [http://cgi2.nhk.or.jp/michi/cgi/detail.cgi?dasID=D0004200021_00000 Fushiki Hikiyama Festival in Takaoka][[NHK]](video)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Toyama}}\n\n[[Category:Takaoka, Toyama|*]]\n[[Category:Cities in Toyama Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Japan]]\n[[Category:Port settlements in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = {{raise|0.2em| Takaoka}}\n| native_name             = {{lower|0.1em|{{nobold|{{lang|ja|\u9ad8\u5ca1\u5e02}}}}}}\n| officia